name: Merel Keijzer
position 1: Professor of English Linguistics and English as a Second Language
skills: ['Statistical Analysis of fMRI Data', 'Statistical Analysis Using R', 'Leadership in academic context']
summary:
I am a second language development and bilingualism researcher. I investigate learning and teaching of English as a second language across the lifespan. When a new language is learned, it exerts an influence on earlier learned languages. 

Since 2018, I have been the PI of the Bilingualism and Aging Lab (BALAB), which focuses on bilingualism studies in older adults, most notably the effects of introducing a bilingual experience later in life: what are the cognitive and social effects of teaching older adults a new language?

In my research, I mostly focus on topics that are ideally suited for knowledge dissemination and directly touch on societal issues: can you ever lose your mother tongue? What are the best ways to teach English at secondary school? What are the major challenges western society faces the coming decades with an increasingly aging population, many speakers of whom have a culturally and linguistically diverse background?  

I see university teaching to be inextricably linked to research: already at the BA level, students should see the research their lecturers do, to place their textbooks into perspective. I view teaching as fully on a par with research as to university staff’s premier tasks. Student evaluations for my courses reflect my goal of constantly innovating existing courses, for instance by adding more recent research papers to the course readings list but also through constantly looking for new activating teaching methods such as the use of knowledge clips and flipped classrooms.
